The article discusses the joint commitment between the Government of Kenya and the Government of the United States of America to promote good governance and anti-corruption efforts in Kenya. The two governments recognize the importance of democracy, rule of law, integrity, and good governance. They have implemented various reforms over time to improve transparency and accountability in public affairs. The governments commit to working together to combat corruption in Kenya and plan to meet quarterly to review progress. They intend to focus on four action areas: deepening partnerships for good governance, institutionalizing integrity and anti-corruption mechanisms, implementing and reinforcing international anti-corruption initiatives and standards, and expanding the use of technology to reduce opportunities for corruption. The governments also pledge to ensure accountability for corruption and mismanagement by conducting thorough investigations and professionally prosecuting corruption cases, strengthening oversight bodies, and enhancing the capacity of relevant agencies. The article outlines specific measures and initiatives that both governments will undertake to achieve these goals.